l cooperatives, and manufacturing centers that have adapted with the changing times. He focuses on farmers' struggles to recover from the Great Depression well into the 1950s, the cultural redefinition and modernization of the region's image that occurred during the 1950s and 1960s, the growth of secondary and higher education, the decline of small towns, the redeployment of agribusiness, and the rapid expansion of edge cities. Drawing his arguments from extensive interviews and evidence from the towns and counties of the Midwest, Wuthnow provides a unique perspective as both an objective observer and someone who grew up there. Remaking the Heartland offers an accessible look at the humble yet strong foundations that have allowed the region to endure undiminished.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectsxMiddle West. 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszMiddle West. 0aAgriculturexMiddle West. 0aAgriculturezMiddle West. 0aCommunity developmentxMiddle West. 0aCommunity developmentzMiddle West. 0aSocial changexMiddle West. 0aSocial changezMiddle West. 0aSocial planningzMiddle West. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh  aAmerican heartland.  aGarden City.  aGreat Depression.  aKansas.  aMiddle West.  aPolly Spence.  aSmith Center.  aSmith County.  aWild West.  aWilliam F. Cody.  aWorld War II.  aagrarian life.  aagribusiness.  aagriculture.  abiotechnology.  acolleges and universities.  adrought.  adust storms.  aeconomy.  aedge cities.  aeducation.  aeducational attainment.  aexurbs.  afarming.  afarms.  afarmsteads.  afeedlots.  afood production.  afriendliness.  aheartland.  ahospitality.  ahousing developments.  aindustrial sector.  aingenuity.  aland.  alandownership.  alandscape.  aliteracy.